This is a depressing question for several reasons, the primary being that it should've been settled on September 30th when the CDC elected to extend the 'no sail' order until February. This decision was overruled by the White House, which likely feared consequences in the swing state of Florida if it were to be implemented. Now, however, we are perhaps days away from reaching peak daily COVID numbers for the year, are back to 1000 people dying each day from the virus, and still have no mitigation or reactionary plans in place on a national level. Therefore, this question is no longer about what is right, but which is more powerful: the scientific community or the President of the United States? The right decision is clear, but the wrong decision is possible. Carnival itself has decided not to resume until December, but its impossible to say what the situation might look like at that point.

On September 21, two North American cruise companies — Royal Caribbean Group (RCL) and Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings (NCLH) — submitted recommendations to the U.S. Centers for Disease Control from their jointly-created Healthy Sail Panel, comprised of government officials and infectious disease experts. I don’t expect any cruises to depart from the continental USA by end of year. Carnival are selling a number of boats right now to sustain a prolonged market downturn. For this to happen (i.e. any cruise to depart in the US) two things need to happen: - a sustained reduction in covid cases to be observed. Right now we see a surge in cases, especially Florida which is a popular departure location. Such a reduction may occur in a month or two (October) or the autumn weather might even bring a second wave of pandemic, thus delaying the cruise industry restart. I assign 33% chance that October time brings a definitive reduction in covid cases in the US. - second condition is that other countries (Caribbean for southern departures or Canada, for Seattle departures) observe a similar improvement in covid cases, that allows them to open their ports. I assign the same probability to that. - finally, consumer confidence has to have returned to confining themselves in cruise ships. We are talking about relatively wealthy retirees. They will take their time to accept to take this risk. This means that with even a 40% capacity, the cruise ship is unlikely to be economic to sail. I assign a 50% chance to demand being there for at least one ship to sail, even when the 33% above has occurred. Overall, I think this bring the cumulative probability to about 17% for anything before January.

Updated 20200803: I previously forecast that pssenger health would be an issue for cruising. In addition to what appears to be a second wave of Covid 19 in many countries, cruiselines that have restarted cruises have struggled to ensure the health of passengers. This is not likely to increase paying passengers confidence. Updated 20200731: Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings has suspended all cruises including subsidiaries, until 1 November 2020. Thus, they're likely to avoid cruising for a while. Much like shopping centres are being avoided. This appears to be confirmed by this article https://reut.rs/2P690Ui. In additon to the health concerns highlighted in this article, it clarifies the need for cruises operating out of contiental USA to comply with requirements of the ports of call intended and obtain approval from such ports. Hence, the no-sail order applicable to USA based ships is not the only criterion, albeit many companies has removed parts of the fleet from USA waters. Obtaining clearances from ports to be visited is also a requirement and that may not be forthcoming depending on pandemic or other conditions at thos ports. They're breeding grounds for COVID if it makes it aboard, and what cruise is really going to be that desirable that requires a quarantine before, testing during, and will never allow you off the boat.

Social distancing is next to impossible on a vessel. Passageways, deck space, dining, embarkation etc. present all sorts of logistical difficulties. I also cannot imagine any port, foreign or domestic allowing passengers to visit shore attractions. That means only a cruise that circles around the ocean, depressing overall demand for cruises. As for the promise of rapid testing, the current false negative rate combined with even a 25% occupancy rate put the potential numbers of infected, but asymptomatic passengers and crew at levels that are simply untenable.

f there is accurate rapid testing is available (and we should see much progress in this area in the next few months), then they could test everyone before they board and keep everyone at sea for the entire cruise.
